 for bestpractices and # File Upload & OCR Ingestion

## Overview
Implement a robust, secure File Upload & OCR Ingestion feature that enables teachers (or parents on behalf of their child) to upload documents and photos, automatically transcribe text via OCR, store files securely in S3-compatible storage with signed URLs, scan for viruses, and provide a manual correction UI for OCR results. The system should support chunked uploads, concurrency handling, metadata indexing for search, access control (owner or shared users), and be integrated with the existing StudySpark project flow (pages: page_p006, page_p007, page_p008). All data ingestion should be resilient to null/undefined values and guarded against runtime errors per the project’s safety standards.

---

## Components to Build
1) File Upload Service
- Functionality: chunked file upload, resumable uploads, concurrency control, Signed URLs for upload/download, client-side progress tracking.
- Storage: S3-compatible object storage (e.g., AWS S3, MinIO) with per-file keys and metadata.
- Virus scanning: Integrate a server-side virus scanning pipeline (e.g., ClamAV) triggered on upload completion or streaming pipeline.
- Metadata: Persist file metadata (filename, size, mime type, ownerId, uploadedAt, permissions, ocrStatus, ocrConfidence, ocrTextFragment, etag, storageKey, signedUrls).
- Security: Enforce access controls, temporary signed URLs with appropriate expiry, and validation of file types and size.
- OCR integration: On upload complete, call OCR service (Google Cloud Vision or equivalent) to extract text, confidence scores, and bounding boxes if needed; store results in metadata for search and human review.
- Error handling: Retry policies, circuit breakers, and robust fallback to manual transcription UI if OCR fails.

2) OCR Ingestion Engine
- OCR Processor: Orchestrate OCR calls (primary: Google Cloud Vision OCR or equivalent; fallback: open-source OCR like Tesseract via a service).
- Output model: structured transcription data including detected text, confidence scores, language hints, blocks/paragraphs, and layout metadata.
- Caching: Cache OCR results to avoid reprocessing duplicates; use file fingerprint or etag as cache key.
- Local correction: Expose a manual correction UI that loads OCR results and allows users to edit text, correct misrecognized characters, and adjust bounding text segments.
- Post-processing: Normalize text (line breaks, whitespace), detect and correct common OCR artifacts, and generate searchable text blobs.
- Data persistence: Update file metadata with ocrText, ocrConfidence, ocrStatus (pending/in-progress/completed/failed/corrected).

3) Manual Correction UI
- UI Components: Text editors with per-paragraph editing, inline spell-check hints, and highlight differences from OCR output.
- Review workflow: Allow users to approve, correct, or request edits; save corrected transcription as final or as a revision.
- Collaboration: Support per-file revision history and audit trail; track who made corrections and when.
- Validation: Ensure corrected text is stored safely, with versioning, and that the final transcription is indexed for search.

4) Metadata & Search Indexing
- Data Model: Define robust metadata for each uploaded file: id, filename, size, mimeType, ownerId, uploadedAt, permissions, ocrStatus, ocrConfidence, ocrText, ocrVersion, storageKey, etag, signedUrls, tags, relatedStudyId, childProfileId, subject, and any custom fields.
- Search: Implement indexing (e.g., with a dedicated search service or database full-text search) on filename, OCR text, tags, owner, and related study metadata.
- Index resilience: Guard against null values; ensure arrays are initialized safely.

5) API Layer
- REST/GraphQL endpoints: 
  - File upload initiation (create/upload session), chunked upload endpoints, and finalization.
  - Signed URL retrieval endpoints for upload and download.
  - OCR status query and OCR results retrieval.
  - Correction submission/update endpoints.
  - Metadata query/list/search endpoints.
  - Access control checks and user-scoped listing.
- Validation: Validate request payloads, file types, sizes, and user authorization on every endpoint.
- Rate limiting and retries: Implement idempotent operations for chunked uploads; protect against abuse.

6) Security & Access Control
- Authentication: Integrate with existing auth (likely via session tokens or JWT) to identify owner and collaborators.
- Authorization: Ensure only owner or shared users can access each file; enforce view/edit permissions for OCR corrections.
- Data protection: Encrypt sensitive fields at rest if applicable; ensure signed URLs have short lifetimes and scoped permissions.
- Logging: Audit access, uploads, OCR actions, and corrections for security and compliance.

7) Frontend UI Pages Integration
- page_p006: File Upload & OCR Ingestion main interface (upload area, status dashboard, OCR progress).
- page_p007: OCR Correction & Review screen (manual transcription editor with per-paragraph corrections).
- page_p008: File & Study Management (filters, search, share and permissions, and integration with study creation).
- Shared components: Upload dropzone, progress bars, chunked upload progress, signed URL download links, OCR results viewer, correction editor, and file metadata cards.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack compatibility: React (with hooks), TypeScript, state management (e.g., Context/Redux), and existing design system.
- Components and pages:
  - UploadDropzone: drag-and-drop area; support for selecting multiple files; show per-file progress; chunked upload visualization; handle retries.
  - UploadChunker: client-side chunked uploader implementing concurrency, chunk size configurability, and resumable uploads; uses signed upload URLs.
  - FileCard/ListView: display file name, size, uploadedAt, OCR status, owner, and quick actions (download, view OCR results, edit corrections).
  - OCRResultViewer: show raw OCR text with highlighted segments, confidence indicators, and search highlight within text.
  - CorrectionEditor: text editor with per-paragraph editing, diff view against OCR, versioning, and save/publish actions.
  - FileDetailModal: shows all metadata, signed URLs, and history.
  - Access control controls: manage sharing with other users, roles, and permission toggles.
  - Search & Filters: by filename, OCR status, owner, date, tags, and subject.
- Data safety: Ensure all array operations guard against null/undefined:
  - Initialize arrays with useState<Type[]>([]) and use data ?? [] patterns where necessary.
  - Guard map/filter/reduce with Array.isArray checks or (items ?? []).map(...) patterns.
- API integration: 
  - Use fetch/axios with strict typing; validate API responses via Array.isArray checks.
  - Use nullish coalescing for optional fields; guard against undefined data before rendering.
- UX considerations:
  - Real-time progress indicators for chunked uploads.
  - Clear error states with actionable retry options.
  - Keyboard accessibility, proper aria labels, and color contrast adherence per design system.

### Backend
- Tech stack: Node.js/Express or NestJS (or your existing backend), with a SQL/NoSQL database as appropriate (PostgreSQL recommended for structured metadata and indexing).
- Storage & OTP:
  - S3-compatible storage integration with multipart upload support.
  - Implement storage keys per file, metadata, and per-upload chunk handling.
  - Signed URL endpoints for secure upload/download with expiry.
- Virus scanning:
  - Trigger virus scan upon finalization or streaming upload completion; reject infected files and provide actionable feedback to frontend.
- OCR integration:
  - Service abstraction to support primary (Google Cloud Vision) and fallback OCR flows.
  - Asynchronous OCR job orchestration (queue-based) with status updates (pending, in_progress, completed, failed).
  - OCR results structure: text, blocks, bounding boxes, confidence, language hints.
- Correction workflow:
  - API to submit corrections; store corrected OCR text as a new version; maintain revision history with userId and timestamps.
- Metadata & indexing:
  - Tables/collections for Files, FileVersions, OCRResults, AccessControls, and AuditLogs.
  - Ensure null-safe reads: const row = response?.data ?? []; const items = Array.isArray(row) ? row : [].
- Access control:
  - Implement ACLs: ownerId, sharedUserIds, and permission levels (view/edit).
  - Enforce at API boundary, and include in query filters for listing.
- API endpoints (examples):
  - POST /api/files/init-upload (returns sessionId, fileName, mimeType, size, uploadUrlMap)
  - POST /api/files/upload-chunk (sessionId, chunkIndex, data)
  - POST /api/files/complete-upload (sessionId) -> triggers virus scan, OCR, and metadata creation
  - GET /api/files/:id (metadata and downloadUrl)
  - GET /api/files/:id/ocr (OCR results)
  - POST /api/files/:id/corrections (save corrections)
  - GET /api/files/search (filters, pagination)
  - PUT /api/files/:id/share (share with userId, permissions)
- Validation:
  - Validate input payloads with strict schemas; guard against missing fields.
  - Ensure array inputs are checked with Array.isArray and defaulted to [] when necessary.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - User uploads via frontend → backend receives chunked upload → stores in S3 with metadata → triggers virus scan → upon success, initiates OCR → stores OCR results in DB → frontend shows OCR results and allows manual corrections → corrected text stored as a new version; metadata indexed for search.
- State management:
  - Frontend maintains per-file state: uploadedBytes, totalSize, ocrStatus, ocrConfidence, correctionVersion.
  - Backend emits status updates via polling or WebSockets/real-time events for long-running OCR; ensure fallback if real-time is unavailable.
- Data consistency:
  - Use upsert semantics for file metadata to avoid duplicates.
  - Guard against race conditions in correction edits by versioning and optimistic locking.

---

## User Experience Flow
1) User opens page_p006 (Upload & OCR Ingestion)
2) Drag-and-drop or click to add files (images, PDFs, DOC/DOCX)
3) Client initiates chunked upload; per-file progress bars show; if network hiccups, upload resumes automatically
4) Upon complete upload, backend runs virus scan
5) If clean, OCR processing starts automatically; progress indicator shows OCR status
6) OCR results appear in the UI (text blocks with confidence scores)
7) User reviews OCR results in Correction UI (page_p007):
   - Edit text in-paragraph or inline; compare with OCR; save as corrected version
   - Option to approve as-is or request changes
8) Metadata appears in page_p008 with searchability and filters
9) User can share files with other users, or organize into folders/studies
10) AI study builder can reference the uploaded content as context for generating tailored study sets

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models (schemas)
  - File
    - id (UUID)
    - filename (string)
    - mimeType (string)
    - size (number)
    - ownerId (string)
    - uploadedAt (timestamp)
    - storageKey (string)
    - etag (string)
    - permissions (array of userIds or ACL)
    - ocrStatus (enum: pending|in_progress|completed|failed|corrected)
    - ocrConfidence (number)
    - ocrText (string) // latest or final corrected text
    - ocrVersion (number)
    - signedUploadUrl (string, ephemeral)
    - signedDownloadUrl (string, ephemeral)
    - tags (array)
    - relatedStudyId (string or null)
  - FileVersion
    - id
    - fileId
    - version (number)
    - ocrText (string)
    - createdBy (userId)
    - createdAt
  - OCRResult
    - fileId
    - blocks: [{ text, confidence, boundingBox }]
    - fullText: string
    - language
    - words: [{ text, confidence, boundingBox }]
  - AccessControl
    - fileId
    - userId
    - permission (view|edit)
  - AuditLog
    - id
    - fileId
    - action (upload|scan|ocr_complete|correction_saved|share|download)
    - actorId
    - timestamp

- API Endpoints (example)
  - POST /api/files/init-upload
    - body: { filename, mimeType, size, relatedStudyId? }
    - returns: { sessionId, uploadUrlMap: { chunk0, chunk1, ... }, fileId }
  - POST /api/files/upload-chunk
    - body: { sessionId, chunkIndex, data (binary/base64) }
  - POST /api/files/complete-upload
    - body: { sessionId }
  - GET /api/files/:id
    - returns: File metadata
  - GET /api/files/:id/ocr
    - returns: OCRResult
  - POST /api/files/:id/corrections
    - body: { correctedText, version }
  - GET /api/files/search?query=&filters=&page=&size=
  - PUT /api/files/:id/share
    - body: { userId, permission }

- Security
  - Authentication: Bearer token or session-based; token must be validated on each request.
  - Authorization: Verify that the requesting user is the owner or has explicit share rights.
  - Signed URLs: Use time-limited, permission-scoped signed URLs for uploads/downloads; ensure URL generation is secure and revocable.
  - Input Validation: Validate all inputs; protect against injection; sanitize OCR text before indexing.

- Validation
  - On API responses, use: const data = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Use data ?? [] in cases where Supabase-like responses return null
  - Guard all array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Ensure useState defaults: const [files, setFiles] = useState<FileMeta[]>([])

